e grouped in three parts, ranging from a conceptual framework to case descriptions rich with illustrations. They provide a valuable service in exploring the nature and significance of social space and particular aspects of its contemporary distribution and contestation. The book addresses a topic that is intrinsically interdisciplinary. Questions of space are examined from a rich variety of disciplinary perspectives in a welcome range from urban planning to political philosophy, shedding a good deal of light in the process. The issues in focus include the dichotomies of public and private space, discussion of rights and duties with regard to the use of space, or conflicts over its allocation. Well reasoned and presented discussion is offered from the perspective of basic values and rights. The policy issue of institutional recognition of the specifics of (minority community) identity is raised in opposition to abstract distributive accounts of justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aCities and townsxSocial aspects. 0aMulticulturalism. 0aSpace. 0aToleration. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh  aMulticulturalism, Politics of religion, Religion, Romanies, United Kingdom, United States, Urban studies.1 aBanerjee, Tridib, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiale, Enrico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCeva, Emanuela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakravarty, Surajit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Felicity Hwee-Hwa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiesa, Francesco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiodelli, Francesco, econtributor.4ctb4https